  "prompt": "What is the value of [math]\\sqrt [i\\pi ] {-1}[/math]?",
  "response": "To evaluate the expression \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\), we can interpret it as:\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{\\frac{1}{i\\pi}}\n\\]\n\nFirst, express \\(-1\\) in its exponential form using Euler's formula:\n\n\\[\n-1 = e^{i\\pi + 2k i\\pi} \\quad \\text{for any integer } k\n\\]\n\nNow, raise both sides to the power of \\(\\frac{1}{i\\pi}\\):\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{\\frac{1}{i\\pi}} = \\left( e^{i\\pi + 2k i\\pi} \\right)^{\\frac{1}{i\\pi}} = e^{\\frac{i\\pi + 2k i\\pi}{i\\pi}} = e^{1 + 2k}\n\\]\n\nHere, \\(k\\) is any integer, reflecting the multi-valued nature of the complex logarithm.\n\n**Principal Value:**\nFor \\(k = 0\\):\n\n\\[\n(-1)^{\\frac{1}{i\\pi}} = e^{1} = e\n\\]\n\n**All Possible Values:**\nIncluding all branches, the values are given by \\(e^{1 + 2k}\\) for any integer \\(k\\).\n\n**Conclusion:**\nThe principal value of \\(\\sqrt[i\\pi]{-1}\\) is \\(e\\).\n\n**Answer:** Its principal value is Euler\u2019s number e. All possible values are e\u00b9\u207a\u00b2k for each integer k.",
